    'how-to-edit-tiktok-videos': `Tiktok isn't about "cinema". It's about retention. If you edit a TikTok like a movie, it will flop. I've analyzed hundreds of viral videos, and they all follow a specific editing pattern.

Learning **how to edit TikTok videos** depends on understanding the algorithm. Here is the framework I use.

## The "1-Second Hook" Rule

You have exactly 0.8 seconds to stop the scroll.
**Bad Hook:** "Hey guys, today I'm going to show you..." (Swipe)
**Good Hook:** "I bet you didn't know this iPhone trick." (Pause)

When editing, always start your video with:
1.  **Motion:** The screen should be moving immediately.
2.  **Text:** A big, bold question or statement.

## The Best Editor? (It's CapCut)

Don't use the built-in TikTok editor for anything complex. It glitches, and you lose your work.
Use **[CapCut](https://www.capcut.com/)**. It's free (mostly), and it has features that TikTok's editor lacks.

**My CapCut Workflow:**
1.  **Import:** Add all my clips.
2.  **Rough Cut:** Trim everything tight. No breathing pauses.
3.  **Captions:** Use "Auto Captions". Viral videos *always* have captions for people watching without sound.
4.  **Effects:** Add *one* zoom or shake every 3-5 seconds to reset the viewer's attention span.

## Viral Editing Techniques

**1. The "Millennial Pause" Removal**
Start speaking the *instant* the video starts. Most people have a slight delay after hitting record. **Cut that out.**

**2. Music Sync**
Don't just slap music on top. Cut your video so the scene changes *on the beat* of the song. It feels satisfying to watch.

> **Need Sounds?** TikTok removes copyrighted music all the time. Check out our [Royalty Free Music](../store?category=Music) if you want customized audio that won't get muted.

**3. Format Matters**
*   **Resolution:** 1080x1920 (Vertical)
*   **Safe Zones:** Don't put text at the bottom (caption area) or right side (like/share buttons). Keep text generally in the middle-top.

## Final Tip: The Loop

The secret to 100%+ watch time is the **Loop**.
End your sentence in a way that flows back into the start.
*   **End:** "...and that is exactly..."
*   **Start:** "...why you should edit like this."

When it loops, it sounds like one continuous thought. Viewers watch it twice without realizing.`,

    'good-video-editing-computer-system': `I've built 10+ editing PCs in my life. I've also wasted thousands on parts I didn't need. The biggest lie in the industry? "You need the most expensive graphics card."

Building a **good video editing computer system** doesn't require a NASA budget in 2024. Here is the real truth about building a workload-crushing editing machine.

## The Hierarchy of Parts

If you had $1000, here is how I would spend it:
1.  **CPU (Processor):** This is 60% of the battle. Video encoding is CPU intensive.
    *   *Intel:* Core i5-13600K or better.
    *   *AMD:* Ryzen 7 7700X or better.
    *   *RAM (Memory):**
    *   *16GB:* The bare minimum.
    *   *32GB:* The sweet spot.
    *   *64GB:* Overkill unless you do After Effects.
3.  **Storage (SSD):** NEVER edit off a Hard Drive (HDD).
    *   Get an **NVMe M.2 SSD** (Samsung 980 Pro or similar). It loads footage instantly.
4.  **GPU (Graphics Card):** You don't need an RTX 4090.
    *   An RTX 3060 (12GB VRAM) is amazing value. VRAM matters more than pure power for video.

## Build vs Buy?

**Build it yourself.**
*   **Why:** You save 20%. You know how to fix it if it breaks. And it's fun.
*   **Difficulty:** It's "Adult Lego". If you can use a screwdriver, you can build a PC.

## Mac vs PC?
*   **Get a Mac (Mac Mini / [Mac Studio](https://www.apple.com/mac-studio/))** if you just want to plug it in and work. The M2/M3 chips are incredible for editing.
*   **Get a PC** if you want to game on the side, or if you need maximum raw power for 3D work ([Blender](https://www.blender.org/)/Unreal).

## Summary
Don't let RGB lights distract you. Spend your money on a good CPU and fast storage. That's what actually makes the timeline smooth.`,

